It means that the compiler encountered an object  (e.g. an array) that was defined but not  instantiated.  There are many reasons for it.  Sometimes you get it because you are calling on a game object too early before the game has had a chance to instantiate it.  Sometimes its in code you created because you forgot to instantiate your own object.```class example
{
    array<string> myarray;  // this is the definition. It tells the compiler what myarray will be but doesn't create it

    void init()
    {
         myarray = new array<string>;  // this is the instantiation.  It tells the compiler to create the object, reserve memory for it, etc    
    }

    void usemyarray()
    {
        myarray.Insert("Now I can use the array because it has been instantiated");  // This line throw a null pointer error if you did not do the instantiation step.
    }
}```

